## Ecology and behaviour

The dietary habits of the [Arctic tern](/Arctic_tern) are, predictably, somewhat fluid, adapting to both geographical location and seasonal availability, but the underlying principle remains consistent: it is overwhelmingly [carnivorous](/Carnivore). In the vast majority of cases, its sustenance comes from small [fish](/Fish) or various marine [crustaceans](/Crustacean) [12] [24]. Fish [species](/Species) constitute the most critical component of its diet, accounting for a greater proportion of the total [biomass](/Biomass) consumed than any other food source. The preferred prey fish are typically immature (one to two-year-old) shoaling [species](/Species) such as [herring](/Herring), [cod](/Cod), [sandlances](/Sandlance), and [capelin](/Capelin) [13]. Among the diverse marine [crustaceans](/Crustacean) that form part of its diet are [amphipods](/Amphipod), various [crabs](/Crab), and plentiful [krill](/Krill). On occasion, these opportunistic birds will also consume [molluscs](/Mollusc), marine worms, or even [berries](/Berry) when available, and in their northern breeding grounds, they are not above supplementing their diet with [insects](/Insect) [34].

[Arctic terns](/Arctic_tern) employ a distinct foraging technique, sometimes executing shallow dips to the water's surface to snatch prey swimming just beneath. When breeding, they may also engage in aerial pursuits, deftly chasing [insects](/Insect) on the wing [34]. It is also theorized, rather amusingly given their diminutive stature, that [Arctic terns](/Arctic_tern) may occasionally engage in [kleptoparasitism](/Kleptoparasitism)—the act of stealing food from other animals. This involves swooping aggressively at other birds to startle them into releasing their freshly caught prey [34]. Several [species](/Species) are targeted in these audacious raids, including conspecifics (other [Arctic terns](/Arctic_tern)), other tern [species](/Species) (like the [common tern](/Common_tern)), and even some [auk](/Auk) and [grebe](/Grebe) [species](/Species) [26]. Apparently, no one is safe from a hungry tern with an attitude.

While nesting, [Arctic terns](/Arctic_tern) find themselves particularly vulnerable to predation by opportunistic cats and a variety of other terrestrial animals [12]. Beyond merely competing for prime nesting real estate, the larger [herring gull](/American_herring_gull) poses a significant threat, unhesitatingly stealing both [eggs](/Egg_(biology)) and fragile hatchlings. The naturally camouflaged [eggs](/Egg_(biology)) offer some degree of protection, as do the strategic selection of isolated nesting sites [36]. Scientists have even experimented with erecting bamboo canes around tern nests, and while they observed fewer predation attempts in these "caned" areas compared to control zones, the canes did not ultimately reduce the probability of successful predation once an attempt was made [40]. It seems some predators are simply too determined. While out foraging, [skuas](/Skua), gulls, and other tern [species](/Species) will frequently harass [Arctic terns](/Arctic_tern), attempting to steal their hard-won food [41]. A bird’s life, it seems, is a constant struggle.

