## Conservation status

The global population of the [Arctic tern](/Arctic_tern) is estimated to exceed two million individuals, with a significant portion—more than half—residing in Europe. Its breeding range is, as previously established, remarkably vast. And while the overall population is thought to be in a state of gradual decline, the [species](/Species) is currently assessed as a [species of least concern](/Species_of_least_concern) by the [IUCN](/International_Union_for_Conservation_of_Nature) [1]. A testament to its resilience, or perhaps simply the sheer number of them, making a decline less immediately catastrophic.

[Arctic terns](/Arctic_tern) are among the [species](/Species) afforded protection under the [Agreement on the Conservation of African-Eurasian Migratory Waterbirds](/AEWA) [42], a small comfort for a bird that effectively ignores human-drawn borders.

Historically, the population in [New England](/New_England) suffered significant reductions in the late nineteenth century, a direct consequence of relentless hunting for the insipid millinery trade [26]. Exploitation, unfortunately, persists in western [Greenland](/Greenland), where the [species'](/Species) population has seen a drastic decline since 1950 [43]. In [Iceland](/Iceland), the [Arctic tern](/Arctic_tern) was regionally uplisted to Vulnerable as of 2018, a worrying development primarily attributed to the catastrophic collapse of [sandeel](/Sandeel) (*[Ammodytes](/Ammodytes)* spp.) stocks [44]. It seems even the most resilient travelers are not immune to the consequences of ecosystem collapse.

At the more southerly limits of their extensive range, the [Arctic tern](/Arctic_tern) has indeed experienced a reduction in numbers. A significant factor contributing to this decline is a critical lack of available food [25]. However, much of these birds' breeding range is incredibly remote, far from human interference, and across the [species](/Species) as a whole, there is no apparent, widespread negative trend [34]. The [Arctic terns'](/Arctic_tern) dispersal patterns are demonstrably affected by changing climatic conditions [45]. Their ability to forage successfully in their Antarctic wintering grounds is intrinsically linked to sea-ice cover, but unlike sedentary breeding [species](/Species), they possess the remarkable flexibility to relocate to different areas if necessary. This adaptability makes them a valuable control [species](/Species) for scientists investigating the broader impacts of [climate change](/Climate_change) on less mobile breeding populations [46].

## Cultural depictions

The [Arctic tern](/Arctic_tern), despite its unassuming appearance, has managed to grace the [postage stamps](/Postage_stamps) of several countries and dependent territories. These territories include [Åland](/%C3%85land), [Alderney](/Alderney), and the [Faroe Islands](/Faroe_Islands), while sovereign nations like [Canada](/Canada), [Finland](/Finland), [Iceland](/Iceland), and even [Cuba](/Cuba) have featured it [47]. A surprisingly diverse fan club for a bird that just wants to be left alone to migrate.

In a moment of questionable comedic genius, the [Arctic tern](/Arctic_tern) was prominently featured in a sketch on the improv comedy television show [Whose Line Is It Anyway?](/Whose_Line_Is_It_Anyway%3F_(American_TV_series)), involving the familiar faces of [Colin Mochrie](/Colin_Mochrie) and [Ryan Stiles](/Ryan_Stiles) [48]. During this particular sketch, Colin, with his characteristic deadpan delivery, suggested that the call of the [Arctic tern](/Arctic_tern) bore an uncanny resemblance to the name of the popular boy band, the [Backstreet Boys](/Backstreet_Boys). One can only assume the terns were not amused.